Where possible, avoid using the dryer and hang your clothes out to dry. A powered clothes dryer is one of the least energy-efficient appliances in any household, whereas a clothesline or clothes rack is naturally solar powered. Line drying ensures really clean and beautiful smelling clothes and linens. It also is a great way to end a cold wash, as the sun bleaches any germs right out of the fabrics. Did you know you can put sheets on the bed while they're still wet? It sounds a bit strange, but cotton sheets are thin fabric, and they will dry very quickly if left uncovered. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/85/Save-Energy-in-the-Laundry-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Save-Energy-in-the-Laundry-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/85/Save-Energy-in-the-Laundry-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Save-Energy-in-the-Laundry-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

While people often used clothespins to hang on a line, you can save time and energy and dry more clothes if you put them on hangers, then place them on the line and hold them in place with a clothespin to anchor the hanger to the line{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d2/Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-13.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-13.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d2/Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-13.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-13.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you are hanging clothes outside, hang the heavy items at the ends of the line and smaller, shorter items in the middle{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-14.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-14.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-14.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-14.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A folding indoor clothes rack is enough for a load of socks and underwear. It's indoors, so won't get you in trouble with the apartment complex or homeowners' association, and it will dry laundry even if it's raining outside. Dry your clothes on clothing rods in doorways. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-4.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-4.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Air dry socks and underwear even if you don't like to air dry the rest. It's easier on the elastic, and it doesn't matter if your underwear is wrinkled. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e7/Save-Energy-in-the-Laundry-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Save-Energy-in-the-Laundry-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e7/Save-Energy-in-the-Laundry-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Save-Energy-in-the-Laundry-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":344,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":568.9560439560439,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

When hang drying towels, fold them in half and pin to hangers. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/17/Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-8.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-8.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/17/Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-8.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Laundry-Like-Grandma-Step-8.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
